ok, first mistake: on these small 4 bangers and turbos you dont put the the pedal to the floor! Subtley is the order of the day. Be gentle  and patient on the throttle and you will be rewarded. Secondly, Nissan finally got the trans programming down. Silky smooth and responsive in auto or manual mode. You have three choices: 1 - auto drive mode, 2 - auto sport drive mode, 3 - manual mode with the paddles. Shifts are quick and responsive in all modes.
the trick in manual mode is to "milk" the throttle as you would with a stick shift trans. Its not a DSG! Also, it does take some practice to use the paddles correctly. Most dont know how to use them properly.   Nissan is not ignorant. They are of  a very sporting mentality. Always were.  This is a huge step foreward.

I won't say I hate this trend, but I hate this trend of manufacturers making 4 cyl turbo engines without making an alternative v6 model... I would appreciate if Manufacturers made both. 4 cylinder turbo engines are only good if you lease them because the engine naturally won't last as long. The engine is more stressed meaning it wears and tears quicker.  a v6 doesn't have to try as hard to cruise at 80mph or speed up to 50mph from a light than a 4 cylinder, meaning less strain over time. In the same comparison a v8 doesn't have to try nearly as hard as a v6. This new fad of 4 cylinder turbo just to please the market and crunch numbers for EPA ratings is a disaster. 4 cyl turbo is no good unless you plan on leasing the car and moving on a few years later. No the money you save on gas is not going to be nearly enough to forego maintenance costs. Not only is the engine more stressed but now you have another component yeah, the TURBO to deal with. This is such a cash-grab against the consumer. Most people don't know that if you drive a car hard and park it. You have to let it idle for a few minutes so the oil can cool down, other-wise you damage the turbo because the oil runs super-hot. Common drivers are unaware of this, and so this turbo fad is just costing them more money due to ignorance in terms of taking care of an engine.

It sounds terrible, and I think Nissan is making a BIG mistake with their all CVT lineup.  Their problems with this transmission are widely known to those of us who read enthusiast magazines or watch the related videos.  I know that they are doing it for fuel economy purposes, but in my opinion, they should add extra gears instead to a well built transmission.  The fact that it's a CVT, not to mention the known reliability issues with this transmission, would cause me to purchase another brand.  Also, as you may know, Nissan achieves the Variable Compression part by changing a pin's location on the connecting rod.  I just wonder if this will cause problems after 100k miles (or less).  I'm sure that Nissan tested it, but that is a lot of movement within the engine -- and how tough can that pin and its associated mechanism be?  I think Honda, Toyota, and the American manufacturers have a better solution.  Nissan needs to watch itts reputation with itts CVT transmissions or their sales may really be affected.

I just leased a 2019 Altima SL Platinum (my 5th Altima, and 7th Nissan overall).  This is my least favorite Altima ever (I've leased a 2006, 2009, 2013 and 2015 previously, with the 2013 being my favorite car ever).
I'll start with the good - 
1.  there are no packages on the SL model; it's all included.  The technology package, plus a few extra features. 
2.  compact disc functionality is gone.  
3.  Navigation automatically displays what street you're on, if you choose that display (I like to leave the display on which direction my car is going, so I also get street display).


And the bad (I get that most people will disagree with me; these are just preferences). 
1.  Beige leather interior is no longer offered. I settled for the light gray interior, and honestly, it looks like a rental car.  The off-color stitching looks cheap (see 7:46), the dashboard material looks cheap - like something you would get in a rental car.  The interior is very dark, and I really, really loved the black exterior, with the beige leather interior - I thought it looks really classy, and light. Also, there is way more nooks and crannies all over the dash, making it a pain to clean.
2.  The seats are smaller.  Much smaller - maybe 2 inches narrower, and at least an inch less depth.  Also, the seat doesn't go down as far as it used to.  I'm only 5'4" and my head is about 5 inches from the roof.  I feel like I'm sitting on a folding chair; no longer surrounded by those soft, comfy seats of the 2013 and 2015 models. 
3.  the steering wheel is smaller, which feels weird when turning, or pulling into a parking space, or pulling out of a parking space.  Also, when I rest my elbow on the door, my fingers barely touch the steering wheel.   
    Also note at 8:14 the new steering wheel controls - they are all flat, so it makes if difficult to turn the volume up/down, or to dismiss notifications, or to to skip songs, etc. without taking your eyes off the road.   I have to look down every time.  In the 2013 and 2015 models, there was a lever that you could feel for without taking your eyes off the road.  I really miss that.  Same goes for cruise control - all the buttons are flat. 
4.  Less visibility all around.  One of the first things I noticed as I drove the car off the lot was less visibility through the windows.  Less window space compared to the 2013 and 2015 models .  The back window seems shorter.  When looking over your right shoulder to see if there is a car out the back passenger side window - that is now a bigger blind spot.  But, I think the worst visibility issue is the front window - there is now a camera on the opposite side of the rearview mirror (you can this for a second at 5:57 - see how much window space that camera takes up?  Decreases visibility when you look out the front window to your right). 
5.  too much clutter on the view screen.  You can see what I'm talking about at 6:58. This is the display I use as well.   Note, the time is displayed here - and it's also displayed on the floating screen to your left.  Two time displays!  It drives me nuts. 
6.  Entertainment system presets - if you want to change the channel, you have to use the touchscreen - which means you have to look at the touch screen every time you want to change the channel - you can't feel for the buttons.  This means you have to take your eyes of the road every time.  I don't think they thought this through. 
7.  The Camera - might be the most disappointing change.  Look at the video at 9:08 - that is the default view.  you can press the "camera" button 2 more times to get the standard, full screen view that you get in the 2013 and 2015 models - but you have to press the button twice EVERY TIME YOU PUT THE CAR IN REVERSE.  Every time.  I've had this car for 17 days  and I've already stopped looking at the camera when I back up.  
8 At 9:48 you can see the settings - this is where you need to go to turn off data collection.  It's defaulted to "on" and and various data is sent to Nissan.  I've turned this off once already, and noticed it was back on today.  
9.  the heated seats don't seem to get as warm as in previous models.  Heated steering wheel seems to get a little warmer than previous models. 
10.  Why would you put an electronic parking break lever on the consul?  Who uses it that much, that it needs to take up prime real estate?


I wish Nissan conducted Usability with loyal customers, or even a focus group, or feedback session.  I'm not sure they thought this one through.  I don't know.  I have a feeling I will be in the minority with this.   Also - I hate those LED headlights.  They are blinding. 


Thanks for letting me vent.  I love Nissan, and I am just really, really disappointed.  I should have bought my 2013 Altima 2.5 SL.  It was the perfect car.

replies.commentText: I have a 2018 Sentra sr Turbo.  It shifts like a regular transmission only smoother. I can say its definitely not shit but I also dont beat on it. Instead of punching it just ease into and the engagement is a smooth transition from a stop.

@Edward Enterline They feel smooth, but eventually they crap out even if you drive normally. It doesn't happen to 100% of the cars, but it happens to enough of them for me to spend my money somewhere else. A lot of times, they start making a whining noise that sounds like a supercharger (a known sign of a transmission that's going bad) and start jerking whenever they change "gears" until they finally stop working. There have also been many cases of them just losing all power without warning, essentially leaving the car coasting. These things usually don't happen to a new car like yours, but they do seem to start happening after around 60,000 miles.

@Jose A. Romo my cousins aunt bought a rogue and had the cvt go within 60k miles. Worries me because i like the standard features and price. Im leasing a rogue right now abou 30k miles in and no issues yet and i like the car.

@Derek Berry Well, JATCO CVTs do have an average failure point of around 60,000 miles. They're basically disposable. I do hope your aunt gets rid of it, because it's guaranteed to break again. In your case, well, you're leasing. If it breaks, they have to fix it. You should be alright with that. However, I will still suggest that when your lease is up, you move on to another brand. Nice exterior styling. That's subjective, of course, but given its simplicity, I'd put it near the the Mazda6 and Passat in exterior looks. Better than the Accord (that appears to have been designed by a committee) and the Camry (that looks like the descendant of a 1930's Flash Gordon spaceship.) Have to say though that I'm not a fan of the my-grill-is-bigger-than-yours styling trend. Though the Altima is playing that game, it can't compare to the Camry and especially the (hideous) bass mouth Avalon. 

Otherwise, the Altima strikes me as competent but hardly inspiring. Those of us who don't like CVT's are unlikely to be mollified by "simulated" gears. On the other hand, have to give props to Nissan for not adding insult to injury by adding "simulated" paddle shifters. Would have been amusing to be a fly on the wall when the marketing folks were told that the BIG NEWS this year would be "the world's first variable compression engine in a mainstream sedan." I suspect the meeting was held on a ground floor to prevent injuries when the participants dived out of the windows. AWD might have been a feature to tout. Of the competitors only Subaru and the dying Ford Fusion offer it. But inexplicably Nissan limits its availability to the base engine. How does that make ANY sense? "Check out our AWD! Oh, you wanted the better engine? Sorry."

The interior is OK but hardly distinctive. A button on the steering wheel to turn off/on the complete set of safety features? Huh? Who's going to use it on a regular basis? Otherwise, the only standout feature in the interior is the seats. Badly configured and uncomfortable seats can be a deal breaker but the competition offers perfectly acceptable seats. Do Americans really purchase a car solely because the Altima's seats treat their asses especially well? (Don't answer that.) Other aspects of the interior are no more inspiring. Just one minor cost cutting shortcoming after another. No wireless charging. Cheap plastic in the rear seats, much like the Camry. Plastic wood trim that looks more like plastic than wood. Perforated front seats that do NOT include ventilation?  A complex set of trim levels that mix and match features. Would hate to be the salesperson who has to explain them.

Bottom line? Not as engaging as the Honda or the Mazda6. Same as far as a premium interior is concerned. Not as much room as the Passat or the Honda. Chock full of minor cost cutting. Lots of "you can't get that with this" trim levels. All in all an also ran.

commentText:
I suspect that the actuator to shift the compression ratio takes a little time and maybe increases the delay. I can't imagine that's a low-torque task, so it may take a second to shift to low compression for boost. Granted, I'm sure they can add enrichment while it's shifting to allow boost to come up. 

Anyway, I'm not sold on the complexity of the VC operation, as reducing cylinder "squish" during high boost will increase detonation propensity, requiring further enrichment and/or lower compression vs. an optimized fixed compression engine. Dynamic compression can be varied with variable cam timing and lift without changing the combustion chamber burn characteristics. Regardless, neat to see different things being tried.
Do you prefer this turbo, or the turbo in the latest Mazda 6?

commentText:
The difference between Nissan when they're trying and not is amazing.  

That said, the floating roof is executed terribly and the misaligned handles are ugly.  The new grill looks great, but most people will see the car from the rear or side on the freeway Nissan.

My experience with Nissan has been that they're comfortable and have nicer materials than Toyota, but the build quality is just crap compared to Honda or Toyota.  Parts falling apart in just a few years, insulation poking out, dials making grinding noises....I hope they have seriously worked to address that or it's lipstick on a pig. 

I kind of wish Nissan would trim down their line and focus on quality and R&D instead of having the now redundant Maxima and every size ugly CUV under the sun.  Toyota and Honda are going to overtake them on autonomy soon despite getting in the game much later.  Nissan had the vision, they were talking EVs and autonomy before it was cool, but they made too many poor business decisions to benefit from it.  That's unfortunate, I wanted them to do better than they have.
